You are Cursor AI working inside the `bus` core dispatcher repository. This
module is the top-level CLI dispatcher and must remain minimal.

Sources (BusDK spec, authoritative):
- https://docs.busdk.com/spec/architecture/independent-modules
- https://docs.busdk.com/spec/cli/command-structure
- https://docs.busdk.com/spec/cli/error-handling-dry-run-diagnostics
- https://docs.busdk.com/spec/cli/interactive-and-scripting-parity
- https://docs.busdk.com/spec/data/csv-conventions
- https://docs.busdk.com/spec/data/table-schema-contract
- https://docs.busdk.com/spec/layout/layout-principles
- https://docs.busdk.com/spec/layout/repository-readme-expectations

Purpose and non-goals:
- Purpose: provide a deterministic dispatcher that executes `bus-<command>` from PATH.
- Non-goals: no business logic, no dataset/schema I/O, no Git operations, no network,
  no module-specific flags beyond shared BusDK CLI conventions.

Invocation and behavior:
- Invocation pattern: `bus <command> [args...]` (this module is the dispatcher).
- Dispatch: resolve with `exec.LookPath("bus-" + name)` only, then exec with args
  unchanged, inheriting stdin/stdout/stderr and environment.
- No-args: print a short usage line to stderr, exit 2, and include an available
  commands list if any are discovered.
- Missing subcommand: stderr must start with `bus:` and mention the expected
  `bus-<name>` in PATH, then print usage + available commands; exit 127.
- Subcommand exit codes pass through exactly. Unexpected exec failures return 1
  with a short `bus:` error on stderr.

Subcommand discoverability (for listing only):
- Scan PATH left-to-right. For each directory, list entries (non-recursive).
- Collect executables matching `bus-*` (Windows: `bus-*.exe`); ignore directories.
- Skip missing or inaccessible PATH entries (EACCES/EPERM) silently.
- Deduplicate by subcommand name, preferring the earliest PATH entry.
- Sort subcommand names lexicographically before printing.

Inputs, outputs, and side effects:
- Inputs: CLI args, PATH, environment, stdin.
- Outputs: only diagnostics/usage on stderr and subcommand output pass-through.
- Side effects: process execution only; no file writes or dataset mutations.

Dry-run, diagnostics, and repository checks:
- This dispatcher does not implement `--dry-run` or workspace/Git checks because
  it does not modify data. Subcommands handle those per the CLI spec.
- Keep error messages concise and script-friendly (see CLI error-handling spec).

Quality gates:
- Tests must be hermetic and deterministic (no network).
- Use temp PATH entries and compiled fake subcommands (`go build`) to validate
  dispatch behavior and listing determinism.

Spec mismatches (documented for clarity):
- CLI name: the CLI spec examples use `busdk ...`, while this repo implements
  `bus` as the dispatcher. Follow repo reality here: binary name `bus` and
  subcommand prefix `bus-`.
- Repo checks and `--dry-run`: the CLI spec expects repo detection and dry-run
  for data-modifying modules; this dispatcher does not perform those checks and
  must remain minimal.

